[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Chapter 12 Preface: When Time Itself Is the Signal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few years ago I was sitting in a conference room with the operations team of a mid-sized hospital, looking at their staffing model. They were using a spreadsheet. The spreadsheet computed next month's expected appointment volume by taking the same month last year and multiplying by 1.03. That was it. That was the forecast. There was a column for "adjustments" where the manager could type in a number if she had a hunch about the flu season or a new provider starting. The hunch column was, by their own admission, where most of the actual forecasting accuracy came from. Decades of operations research, two generations of statistical time series methodology, half a decade of deep learning on sequence data, and the production system was last-year-times-1.03-plus-vibes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m I bring this up not to mock the hospital. They were doing their best with what they had, and frankly the spreadsheet was about as accurate as a lot of the more sophisticated systems I've seen since. I bring it up because it captures something important about the state of time series analysis in healthcare. The methods exist. The data exists. The computational infrastructure exists. But the gap between what's possible and what's actually deployed in production, in operating rooms and emergency departments and revenue cycle teams, is enormous. The simplest recipes in this chapter (appointment volume forecasting, supply inventory forecasting) are not technically novel; they've been solved problems in operations research for forty years. They're in the chapter because most healthcare organizations still aren't doing them, and the ROI on actually doing them is huge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The other end of the chapter is a different story entirely. Real-time vital sign trajectory analysis, disease progression modeling, physiological waveform analysis, epidemic forecasting: these are at the frontier. The methods are still evolving, the deployment patterns are still being figured out, and the failure modes are clinically consequential. A vital sign monitor that miscalibrates its trend detection contributes to alert fatigue, which contributes to missed deteriorations, which contributes to deaths. <!-- TODO: verify; alert fatigue and its connection to patient safety incidents have been extensively documented in the patient safety literature, with the Joint Commission and ECRI both flagging it as a top patient safety concern in recent years --> The stakes ramp up fast as you move down the recipe list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What makes time series particularly interesting as a category in healthcare is that *time itself is part of the signal*. In document intelligence, the document is the data. In imaging, the image is the data. In time series, the order matters, the spacing matters, the gaps matter, the rate of change matters, and a value that looks normal in isolation can be alarming in context. A potassium of 4.5 is normal. A potassium of 4.5 in a patient whose previous three values were 3.2, 3.6, 4.1 is a trajectory worth paying attention to. The math we use to detect that trajectory, distinguish it from normal day-to-day fluctuation, decide when to alert, and validate that alerts are useful is what this chapter is about.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## What Time Series Analysis Actually Is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's level-set. "Time series analysis" is a sprawling category that overlaps with statistics, signal processing, control theory, machine learning, and operations research. When people say it in healthcare contexts, they usually mean one of several distinct things, and conflating them is how you end up with the wrong tool for the job.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Forecasting.** Given a series of past observations, predict future values. "How many appointments will we have next Tuesday?" "How much PPE will we use in the next 30 days?" "What's the expected ED census tomorrow morning?" The output is typically a point prediction plus a confidence interval, sometimes a full probability distribution, occasionally a hierarchy of predictions across time and grouping levels. This is the most common interpretation of "time series" in operational settings, and it's where the simple end of this chapter lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anomaly detection.** Given a stream of observations, flag values or patterns that don't fit the expected behavior. This overlaps with Chapter 3 (Anomaly Detection), but the time series version specifically uses temporal structure: not just "is this value unusual" but "is this *change* unusual given the recent trajectory and the expected seasonal pattern." Lab result outlier detection, vital sign trajectory monitoring, and parts of waveform analysis live in this space.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Change point detection.** When did the underlying behavior of the series shift? A patient's blood pressure pattern looked stable for six months, then started drifting upward. When did the drift start? Change point detection methods (CUSUM, Bayesian online change point detection, segment regression) answer this. Useful for identifying when a treatment started working, when a chronic condition started progressing, when a hospital unit's discharge patterns changed after a workflow change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trajectory modeling.** Given a series of measurements, characterize the underlying trajectory: linear decline, exponential decay, sigmoid progression, step changes after intervention. The output is often a model of how the underlying process is evolving, parameterized in clinically meaningful ways. Disease progression modeling lives here: we want to know not just "what will the next eGFR value be" but "what's the patient's individual rate of kidney function decline, and does it match Stage 3 CKD progression or something faster."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **State-space modeling.** Treat the observed series as noisy measurements of an underlying hidden state that evolves over time. The Kalman filter is the classic example; modern Bayesian state-space methods (BSTS, particle filters) generalize it. Useful when you have an explicit model of how the underlying process should behave, plus measurement noise on top. Appears in physiological monitoring (the actual heart rate is a hidden state; the monitor's reading is a noisy observation of it).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sequence modeling and representation learning.** Treat the time series as a sequence and let a neural network learn useful representations. Transformers, RNNs, temporal convolutional networks, foundation models for time series. The recent direction, with mixed results in healthcare. Strong on benchmark datasets, sometimes underwhelming in production where the underlying mechanism is more interpretable than the deep model needs to be.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Survival analysis with time-varying covariates.** When you care not just about predicting a value but predicting the time until an event (admission, readmission, death, disease progression milestone), survival analysis is the right tool, and when the inputs themselves are evolving over time it becomes a time-varying covariates problem. Kaplan-Meier estimators, Cox proportional hazards models, parametric survival models, and modern deep survival methods all live here. This connects back to Chapter 7 (Predictive Analytics) but is intrinsically temporal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Streaming and online algorithms.** When data arrives continuously and you can't wait to process it in batches, the algorithm itself has to be online. Rolling window statistics, exponential weighted moving averages, online change point detection, streaming forecasting. Vital sign monitoring (12.7) and waveform analysis (12.10) require this; appointment forecasting (12.1) does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hierarchical and multi-resolution forecasting.** Healthcare forecasts often need to be coherent across multiple levels. The forecast for the whole hospital should equal the sum of forecasts by service line, which should equal the sum of forecasts by individual unit. Achieving this without the levels contradicting each other is a non-trivial problem with its own literature (top-down, bottom-up, middle-out, optimal reconciliation).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most recipes in this chapter combine several of these. ED arrival forecasting (12.3) combines forecasting with hierarchical decomposition by acuity. Vital sign monitoring (12.7) combines streaming algorithms, anomaly detection, and change point detection. Disease progression modeling (12.8) combines trajectory modeling, survival analysis with time-varying covariates, and Bayesian state-space methods. The architectural choices come from picking the right combination for the problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why Healthcare Time Series Is Uniquely Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you've worked on time series in retail demand forecasting or financial markets, your intuitions will mostly transfer to healthcare and a handful will catastrophically not. Calling out the differences, because every recipe in this chapter bumps into at least one of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Sampling Is Almost Never Regular
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In a stock price series, you have a price every minute the market is open. In an IoT sensor stream, you have a reading every n milliseconds. In healthcare, you have a lab value when somebody ordered a lab. You have a vital sign when a nurse measured it. You have a weight when the patient stepped on a scale. The intervals between observations are not constant, they're not even predictable, and the sampling pattern itself is informative: a patient whose creatinine is being checked every six hours is sicker than one whose creatinine is being checked every six months, and the sampling density is part of the signal whether you wanted it to be or not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This breaks most off-the-shelf time series methods, which assume regularly-spaced observations. You have a few real options: resample to a regular grid (with imputation, which introduces its own assumptions and biases), use methods that natively handle irregular sampling (Gaussian processes, point process models, certain neural architectures), or model the sampling pattern explicitly alongside the values. Each has tradeoffs, and the recipes call out which approach fits which use case. The naive answer (just resample) is often wrong in clinically important ways. A patient who hasn't had labs drawn for two weeks looks "stable" if you carry the last value forward and "unknown" if you handle missingness honestly. The first interpretation can be dangerous.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Stationarity Is a Polite Fiction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A lot of classical time series theory is built on the assumption of stationarity, that the underlying statistical properties of the series don't change over time. In healthcare, almost nothing is stationary. Patient populations shift. Coding practices change. New providers join, old ones leave. A new EHR rollout changes documentation patterns. Insurance contract changes alter referral flows. The pandemic changed everything about every operational time series and broke models that had been working for years overnight. <!-- TODO: verify; the COVID-19 pandemic's disruption of healthcare operational time series was extensively documented, with multiple peer-reviewed papers describing model failure during the early pandemic period and the recovery patterns afterwards -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Treating non-stationarity as a nuisance to be transformed away (via differencing, detrending, seasonal adjustment) handles part of it. The rest you handle by accepting that your model is a hypothesis about the recent past, not a law of nature, and you build in the operational practices (retraining cadence, drift monitoring, manual override capability) that let the system stay useful when reality shifts. Recipes that are honest about this build in monitoring; recipes that aren't break in production six months after launch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Treatment Effects Are the Whole Point and the Whole Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In an industrial demand forecasting problem, you forecast based on historical patterns and don't expect the act of forecasting to change the future. In healthcare, you forecast specifically so somebody can intervene, which means the future you forecast is the future where nobody intervened, which is not the future that actually happens. This sounds philosophical; it has very practical consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A forecast of patient deterioration that triggers a clinical intervention will look "wrong" in retrospect because the deterioration didn't happen, even though the model was correctly predicting what would have happened without the intervention. A forecast of disease progression that informs a treatment decision will look "wrong" if the treatment alters the progression. A model trained on outcomes from patients who all received some standard of care doesn't tell you what happens to patients who don't receive it. Counterfactual reasoning, treatment effect modeling, and causal inference connect to time series forecasting in healthcare in ways they mostly don't in other domains. The recipes that touch clinical decision-making (12.4, 12.7, 12.8) acknowledge this directly; the operational recipes (12.1, 12.2, 12.5, 12.6) mostly don't have to.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Patient-Specific Baselines Beat Population Baselines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A heart rate of 110 is mildly tachycardic in the general adult population. A heart rate of 110 in a patient whose normal resting heart rate is 60 is alarming. A heart rate of 110 in a patient whose normal resting heart rate is 100 is unremarkable. Population-level threshold rules miss patient-specific deteriorations and over-alert on patient-specific normalcy. Most clinical time series recipes need patient-specific baselines, which means you need enough history per patient to establish one, which means the cold start problem is real and persistent. New patients get population-level rules until you accumulate enough data to personalize. The transition has to be designed deliberately; the recipes call out where it lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Alert Fatigue Is the Dominant Failure Mode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A clinical time series system that flags 100 alerts per shift, of which 95 are clinically irrelevant and 5 are real, performs worse in practice than a system that flags 5 alerts per shift, of which 3 are clinically real. The second system is half as sensitive in raw statistical terms and dramatically more useful operationally, because clinicians actually act on the alerts. Once the false positive rate is high enough that clinicians start ignoring the alerts, the sensitivity of the system drops to zero regardless of what the math says. <!-- TODO: verify; alert fatigue and its impact on clinical alert response rates have been extensively documented; key references include studies on physiological monitor alarms in ICU settings and on EHR clinical decision support alert override rates -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This means clinical time series systems have to be tuned not for theoretical optimum performance but for the operational constraint of "how many alerts can the receiving clinician actually attend to." Hard threshold tuning, hierarchical alert prioritization, suppression rules for alerts the clinician already saw and dismissed, and silent monitoring with periodic summaries instead of real-time alerts are all architectural patterns that emerge from this constraint. The simple operational recipes don't have this problem; the clinical recipes (12.7 especially) live and die by it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Forecast Horizon Trades Off With Accuracy in Non-Obvious Ways
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Forecasting tomorrow's appointment volume is much easier than forecasting next quarter's appointment volume. That's intuitive. What's less intuitive is that for some healthcare problems, the medium horizon (weeks to months) is harder than either the short horizon (next day) or the long horizon (annual aggregate). Short horizons are dominated by recent patterns. Long horizons are dominated by stable structural factors. Medium horizons are where seasonal effects, contract changes, and operational shifts haven't fully manifested yet but are starting to influence things, and the model has to reason about a moving regime. The recipes are explicit about which horizons they're useful for, and where the accuracy degrades fast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Hierarchical Coherence Matters and Is Not Free
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A forecast of total hospital census that doesn't equal the sum of unit-level forecasts is a forecast that operations teams can't use, because the unit charge nurse can't act on a number that contradicts the system-level number. Achieving coherence across a forecast hierarchy (system, service line, unit, sub-unit) without sacrificing accuracy is its own problem with its own literature. <!-- TODO: verify; hierarchical forecast reconciliation methods including bottom-up, top-down, middle-out, and optimal MinT reconciliation have a substantial peer-reviewed literature, with Hyndman and others as key contributors --> Most production hospital census systems get this wrong, which is why the unit-level forecasts and the system-level forecasts you see on different dashboards often disagree by clinically meaningful amounts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Real-Time Streaming Adds a Whole Engineering Layer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Forecasting tomorrow's appointment volume can run as a daily batch job. Detecting deterioration in a continuously-monitored patient cannot. The streaming use cases (12.7 vital sign monitoring, 12.10 waveform analysis) need a streaming infrastructure that the batch use cases don't. Late-arriving data, out-of-order events, partial data from intermittent sensors, watermarks for "what time is it now in the system," exactly-once processing semantics, all of these become first-class concerns. Most healthcare time series teams underestimate how much of the work in streaming use cases is the streaming infrastructure rather than the model. The recipes that need streaming say so; the ones that don't, don't.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Regulatory Exposure Climbs Fast With Clinical Claims
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A forecast that informs operational staffing is unregulated software. A model that detects deterioration in a patient and triggers a clinical alert is potentially a regulated medical device under the FDA's Software-as-a-Medical-Device (SaMD) framework. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA SaMD framework and its application to clinical decision support and predictive analytics tools is governed by a combination of the 21st Century Cures Act provisions and the FDA's clinical decision support guidance, with the regulatory boundary depending on whether the software's recommendations are reviewable by a clinician before action --> A waveform analysis system that identifies arrhythmias (12.10) is almost certainly a regulated device. The recipes are explicit about where the regulatory line falls. As a heuristic: if the model output is consumed primarily by clinicians and reviewed before action, you're likely in clinical decision support territory; if it triggers automated action or is consumed directly by patients, you're more likely in device territory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Population Drift Can Mask Itself as Model Decay
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A model that worked great in 2019 and stopped working in 2020 didn't necessarily decay because the model is broken. The population it was modeling changed (in 2020, dramatically). Distinguishing model decay (the same population, the model has stopped predicting it well) from population shift (the population itself changed, the model is now modeling something that no longer matches reality) requires monitoring both the model's predictions and the input distribution itself. Most production healthcare ML systems monitor only the predictions and miss the distribution shift, which is why so many of them silently degrade for months before somebody notices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Progression: Simple to Complex
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This chapter is ordered roughly by clinical risk, integration depth, and methodological sophistication. Quick map:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipes 12.1 to 12.2 (Simple).** Appointment volume forecasting and supply inventory forecasting. Operational, well-understood, abundant data, errors are economic rather than clinical. These are your two- to three-month projects, often with measurable ROI in the first quarter post-launch. They build the operational muscles (data engineering, backtesting, prediction interval calibration, dashboard integration) that the harder recipes depend on. Most healthcare organizations should start here, because the operational pain is real, the methods are mature, and the win is large enough to fund the rest of the program. If your scheduling team is still using last-year-times-1.03 plus a hunch column, this is your starting point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.3 (Simple-Medium).** ED arrival forecasting. Where time series meets operational complexity. Higher variability than scheduled visits, requires forecasting acuity mix not just total volume, sensitivity to weather and community events, and direct connection to staffing and bed management decisions. The technology is straightforward (mostly hierarchical forecasting plus exogenous regressors); the operational integration is where the engineering effort lives. The downstream consumer (the ED charge nurse, the bed coordinator) needs to trust the forecast enough to act on it, which means calibration, monitoring, and explanation matter as much as raw accuracy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.4 (Medium).** Lab result trend analysis. The first recipe in the chapter where the time series is per-patient rather than per-organization, and where the consumer is a clinician rather than an operations team. Patient-specific baselines, irregular sampling, distinguishing clinically meaningful drift from normal variation. Informs clinical monitoring without replacing clinical judgment. The recipe walks through how to establish patient-specific baselines, how to handle the cold start problem for new patients, and how to surface trajectories without contributing to alert fatigue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.5 (Medium).** Hospital census forecasting. Operational forecasting at a level of complexity that exceeds what spreadsheets can handle. Hierarchical structure (system, service line, unit), real-time updating as the day progresses, integration with admissions, discharges, and transfers, length-of-stay variability, and the hard constraint that the unit-level numbers have to add up to the system-level number. The recipe covers hierarchical reconciliation methods explicitly and is candid about how much of the value is in the data engineering and not the model itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.6 (Medium).** Revenue cycle cash flow forecasting. The non-clinical recipe that funds the rest of the time series program at most healthcare organizations. Predicting cash collection timing across multiple payer types with different payment patterns, handling denial and appeals lag, accounting for contract changes, and producing forecasts that the finance team trusts enough to use for working capital decisions. The methods are standard but the data engineering is significant; payer-mix changes and contract amendments break models in ways that cross-validation against historical data won't catch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.7 (Medium-Complex).** Vital sign trajectory monitoring. Where time series meets real-time clinical signal detection. Streaming architecture, patient-specific baselines, distinguishing artifact from real changes, integration with bedside monitors and EHR vital sign streams, alert routing to the right clinician, and explicit calibration against alert fatigue tolerance. The recipe sits at the regulatory edge of "clinical decision support" and pulls on patterns from Chapter 3 (Anomaly Detection) and Chapter 7 (Predictive Analytics) for the deterioration prediction component. Production deployments require clinical validation, IRB-style governance for any pilot phase, and explicit operational protocols for what happens when the system raises an alert.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.8 (Complex).** Disease progression trajectory modeling. Modeling individual patients' disease trajectories over months and years, with sparse and irregular measurements, treatment effects that alter the trajectory, missing data that's not missing at random (sicker patients get sampled more), and outputs that inform treatment decisions. Methodologically rich (mixed-effects models, joint models for longitudinal and survival outcomes, Bayesian hierarchical models, deep state-space models), clinically delicate, and operationally hard to deploy because the validation timeline matches the disease's natural timeline. Budget multiple years for production deployment with clinical validation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.9 (Complex).** Epidemic forecasting. Population-level forecasting with the hardest validation problem in the book: by the time the forecast is testable, the underlying dynamics have shifted. Sparse early signals, behavioral changes that affect transmission, multiple data sources of varying quality (lab confirmations, ED visits, syndromic surveillance, wastewater), and high-stakes communication of uncertainty to public health decision-makers. The recipe is honest about the limits of the methods, the role of mechanistic models versus statistical models, and the operational reality that during an actual outbreak, nobody has time to retrain models from scratch and the methods that work are the ones that were already in production and well-understood.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipe 12.10 (Complex).** Physiological waveform analysis. The bleeding edge of the chapter. ECG, EEG, continuous arterial pressure waveforms, accelerometer streams. Sample rates of hundreds to thousands of Hertz, multi-channel data, signal processing on top of time series modeling, FDA regulation of any diagnostic claim, and ICU workflow integration. The recipe walks through the layered pipeline (signal preprocessing, feature extraction, classification or detection, alerting, clinical review), the build-versus-buy math (most organizations should buy from a regulated vendor for diagnostic claims), and the operational reality that the ICU's existing alarm infrastructure is already overwhelming clinicians, and any new system has to subtract noise rather than add it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You can read the chapter linearly or jump to the recipe that maps to your immediate problem. If you're new to time series as a discipline, the operational recipes will build the mental models that the clinical ones depend on. The data engineering, backtesting discipline, and prediction interval calibration from 12.1 and 12.2 are foundational for every later recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Techniques You'll See
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Quick reference on the technique families, because the names recur:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Classical statistical methods.** ARIMA (autoregressive integrated moving average) and its seasonal variant SARIMA. Exponential smoothing (simple, Holt's, Holt-Winters) and the modern state-space formulation (ETS). Vector autoregression (VAR) for multivariate problems. These are the workhorse methods for operational forecasting. They're well-understood, computationally cheap, interpretable, and surprisingly hard to beat with fancier methods on most healthcare operational time series. The recipes use them where they fit and don't apologize for it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Modern decomposition methods.** Prophet (from Facebook/Meta), STL decomposition, BSTS (Bayesian Structural Time Series). Decompose the series into trend, seasonality, holidays, and special events, model each component, and recompose. Strong on operational forecasting where you have known event calendars (holidays, school schedules, flu season, organizational events). Prophet specifically gets a lot of healthcare adoption because it handles missing data and outliers gracefully and produces sensible defaults out of the box. <!-- TODO: verify; Prophet's adoption in healthcare operational forecasting is widespread but specific adoption metrics are not centrally tracked; the method is described in Taylor and Letham 2018, "Forecasting at Scale" -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gradient-boosted tree models for time series.** Reformulate the time series as a supervised learning problem (lag features, rolling statistics, calendar features, exogenous regressors), then use gradient-boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost). Particularly strong when there are many exogenous variables (weather, scheduled events, capacity changes) and when interactions between features matter. The recipes use this pattern especially for ED arrival forecasting (12.3) and revenue cycle cash flow (12.6).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep learning sequence models.** RNNs (LSTM, GRU), temporal convolutional networks, attention-based models, and transformer-based architectures (Temporal Fusion Transformer, Informer, PatchTST, and the various time-series-specific transformer variants). Strong on benchmark datasets, sometimes underwhelming in production where the data volume is smaller and the underlying mechanism is more interpretable than the deep model needs to be. The recipes use them where they earn their complexity and acknowledge where they don't.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Neural forecasting frameworks.** DeepAR, N-BEATS, N-HiTS, and similar architectures designed specifically for forecasting at scale across many related series. Useful when you have hundreds or thousands of series with shared structure (forecasts per unit, per service line, per supply SKU) and you want a single model that learns from all of them rather than fitting separate models per series. Recipe 12.2 (supply inventory) and 12.5 (hospital census) call out where this pattern fits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **State-space models and Kalman filters.** Treat the observed series as noisy measurements of an underlying hidden state. Useful when you have an explicit physical or physiological model of the underlying process and noise on the measurements. The Kalman filter is the linear Gaussian special case; particle filters and Bayesian state-space methods generalize it. Vital sign monitoring (12.7) uses this pattern explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gaussian processes.** Probabilistic models that handle irregular sampling natively and produce calibrated uncertainty estimates. Computationally expensive at scale (cubic in the number of observations) but the right tool for some clinical use cases, especially when the time series is short, irregular, and you care about quantified uncertainty. Disease progression modeling (12.8) sometimes uses this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Joint models for longitudinal and survival data.** When you care about both predicting the trajectory of a biomarker and predicting time to a clinical event, joint models link the two. Used in disease progression modeling (12.8) when the question is "given this kidney function trajectory, what's the time to dialysis."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Change point detection.** Algorithmic detection of regime shifts in a series. CUSUM, Bayesian online change point detection, segment regression. Used to detect when a patient's pattern shifted, when a hospital's operational regime changed, when a model needs retraining.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anomaly detection on time series.** Connects to Chapter 3. Specifically temporal: not just "is this value unusual" but "is this *change* unusual given the recent trajectory." STL-based anomaly detection, isolation forest with temporal features, autoencoder-based methods, and the various time series-specific anomaly detection algorithms.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hierarchical forecast reconciliation.** Methods that ensure forecasts at different aggregation levels are coherent. Bottom-up (forecast lowest level, sum up). Top-down (forecast top, allocate down). MinT (optimal reconciliation that minimizes prediction error variance). Recipe 12.5 (hospital census) covers this in depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Streaming algorithms.** Online versions of statistical methods that update with each new observation rather than retraining on the full history. Exponential weighted moving averages, online quantile estimation, streaming change point detection. Vital sign monitoring (12.7) and waveform analysis (12.10) require these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Signal processing for waveforms.** Below the time series modeling layer for high-frequency signals: digital filters (low-pass, high-pass, band-pass), Fourier and wavelet transforms, peak detection, QRS detection for ECG, spectral analysis for EEG. Recipe 12.10 (waveform analysis) lives in this territory; the other recipes don't touch it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Probabilistic forecasting and prediction intervals.** Producing distributions over future values, not just point predictions. Quantile regression, conformal prediction, Bayesian methods, and the prediction-interval outputs of methods like Prophet and DeepAR. For clinical use, prediction intervals are often more useful than point predictions, because the clinician's question is "how confident is the system, and is the interval narrow enough to act on" rather than "what's the single best guess."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Backtesting and rolling cross-validation.** The methodology for validating time series forecasts honestly. Standard cross-validation doesn't work because you can't randomly shuffle time. Rolling-origin evaluation, expanding window evaluation, and backtesting against held-out periods are the right techniques. Most production healthcare time series systems get this wrong; the recipes are explicit about it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You don't need all of these for any one recipe. You do need to recognize the vocabulary because the architectural conversations move quickly between methods.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Key Architectural Patterns You'll See Repeatedly
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few patterns compound across the chapter. Calling them out here saves repetition later:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The data pipeline is most of the work.** Across every recipe in this chapter, the modeling step takes weeks; the data engineering takes months. Pulling time-stamped data from EHRs, scheduling systems, billing systems, and bedside monitors. Reconciling time zones, daylight saving boundaries, late-arriving updates, and the difference between event time and ingestion time. Handling backfills when historical data is corrected. Versioning the data so you can reproduce a forecast that was made six months ago. Most healthcare time series projects underestimate the data engineering by an order of magnitude, ship the model, and then spend the next year fixing the data layer in production. The recipes are honest about this and lead with the data engineering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Backtesting before deployment is non-negotiable.** Every operational recipe in this chapter includes a backtesting protocol: train on historical data ending at time T, forecast forward, compare against actuals, roll forward, repeat. The protocol exposes both accuracy degradation and operational issues (the forecast was technically correct but the cadence didn't match decision points; the forecast was right on average but had unbiased errors at specific times of day). Production deployments that skip backtesting in favor of "we'll monitor it after launch" tend to launch and then have a bad first quarter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prediction intervals are part of the deliverable.** Point forecasts without intervals are misleading because they suggest a precision that doesn't exist. The architectures produce intervals (parametric, quantile-based, or conformal), monitor their calibration over time (a 90% interval should contain the actual value 90% of the time, not 70% or 99%), and surface them to downstream consumers in interpretable form. Operations teams can act on "we'll have between 110 and 140 admissions, most likely 125" in ways they can't act on "the forecast is 125."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Backtested calibration of alert thresholds.** Every clinical alerting recipe (12.4, 12.7, parts of 12.10) sets alert thresholds based on a backtested operating point: at this threshold, we would have generated X alerts per shift in the historical data, of which Y would have corresponded to clinically actionable events. The choice of threshold is a deliberate operational decision, not a default, and the recipes show how to surface the tradeoff to the clinical team that has to live with it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Drift monitoring as a first-class system.** Production time series models drift. The architectures monitor not just prediction accuracy but the input distribution, the residual distribution, and the calibration of prediction intervals. When drift exceeds threshold, the system either retrains automatically (where appropriate) or alerts operators (where the change might be operationally meaningful and worth investigating before retraining). Skipping drift monitoring is how production models silently degrade for six months before somebody notices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Retraining cadence matched to the underlying dynamics.** Daily appointments don't change much from week to week; quarterly retraining is fine. ED arrival patterns shift seasonally and during local events; weekly or even daily retraining is appropriate. Vital sign baselines need to update continuously per patient. The retraining cadence is a design parameter, not a default, and the recipes call out the right cadence for each use case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hierarchical forecasting infrastructure.** When the use case requires coherent forecasts across a hierarchy (system, service line, unit), the architecture builds the hierarchy explicitly, runs a reconciliation step that ensures coherence, and serves the reconciled forecasts to downstream dashboards. Skipping this gives you the forecasts-don't-add-up-across-dashboards problem that has plagued hospital census forecasting for decades.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Streaming infrastructure for real-time use cases.** For the streaming recipes (12.7, 12.10), the architecture includes message queues for the incoming data stream, a stream processing framework that handles the windowing and watermarks correctly, an online model that updates incrementally, and a downstream alert routing layer. The infrastructure is more complex than the model. The recipes are explicit about this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Counterfactual handling for clinical decision support.** Models that inform clinical action need to handle the "I forecasted deterioration, the team intervened, deterioration didn't happen" case. The architecture logs the prediction, the intervention, and the outcome separately, so model performance evaluation can distinguish "the prediction was wrong" from "the prediction triggered an effective intervention." Most production systems don't handle this and as a result their accuracy metrics decay misleadingly over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Fallback to simpler models when the complex model fails.** When the deep learning forecast is unavailable (data pipeline broke, model server is down, recent input data is corrupt), the architecture falls back to a simpler model (last week's average, exponential smoothing, ARIMA on a small recent window). Operations teams need a forecast every day; "the model is down" is not an acceptable answer. The simple fallback is part of the production design, not an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous evaluation against operational reality.** Forecasts don't get evaluated only against held-out historical data. The architectures track operational metrics: how often did the forecast trigger a staffing change, did the staffing change look right in retrospect, did the operational team override the forecast and how often were they right to. The model's technical accuracy and the system's operational utility can diverge; the architectures monitor both.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Healthcare-Specific Considerations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Beyond the architectural patterns, a few considerations recur across every recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **HIPAA compliance is foundational, not bolted on.** Every recipe assumes a HIPAA-compliant deployment. BAA with the cloud provider. Encryption at rest (S3 SSE, encrypted databases) and in transit (TLS). Audit logging of every PHI access. Role-based access controls on dashboards and model outputs. Data minimization (don't pull patient identifiers into the forecasting environment if the forecast doesn't need them; aggregate operational data is often less restrictive than patient-level data). The recipes don't repeat this for each one, but it's the floor for all of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Time-stamped data has integrity implications.** Forecasts depend on the accuracy of the timestamps on historical observations. Late-arriving data, retrospective corrections, time zone confusion (UTC versus local versus user's display time), daylight saving boundaries, and the difference between event time and ingestion time all create bugs that are easy to introduce and hard to detect. The recipes flag where this matters and how to handle it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-level time series are PHI; aggregated operational time series are usually not.** The forecasting infrastructure for appointment volume can run in a less-restrictive environment than the infrastructure for vital sign monitoring. Recognizing this distinction lets operational teams move faster on the simple recipes without dragging the full clinical-grade compliance overhead into projects that don't need it. The recipes call out where the data sensitivity boundary falls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical alerts need explicit governance.** Any recipe that generates a clinical alert needs an alert governance structure: who's responsible for tuning the threshold, who reviews the false positives, who's accountable when an alert is missed. The clinical informatics team or equivalent owns this. The architectures include the operational artifacts (alert review dashboards, monthly tuning reviews, clinical sign-off on threshold changes) that the governance requires. Skipping this is how clinical alert systems get rolled back six months after launch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA exposure scales with claim strength.** Operational forecasting is unregulated. Patient-specific clinical predictions consumed by clinicians are clinical decision support (mostly outside FDA regulation if certain conditions are met). <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's December 2022 final guidance on Clinical Decision Support software clarified the conditions under which CDS software is excluded from device regulation, particularly the requirement that the recommendations be reviewable by the clinician before action --> Patient-specific clinical predictions consumed directly by patients, or that drive automated clinical action, are more likely regulated. Diagnostic claims (this waveform indicates atrial fibrillation) are almost always regulated. The recipes call out where the regulatory line falls and what the implications are. Your regulatory team is the authoritative source for your specific deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations apply to time series too.** Forecasting models can produce disparate accuracy across patient subpopulations, and operational forecasting models can amplify access inequities (if the system consistently underforecasts demand for the clinic that serves a Medicaid population, that clinic is consistently underresourced). The recipes that touch patient-facing operations or clinical predictions include subgroup performance monitoring as a launch criterion, not a phase-2 feature.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Documentation of forecasting assumptions.** Forecasts depend on assumptions: the population doesn't shift, the operational process doesn't change, the data continues to mean what it used to mean. When those assumptions break, the forecast breaks, and the operational team needs to know why. The recipes document the assumptions explicitly so when a forecast goes wrong (because the EHR was upgraded, or a contract changed, or a pandemic happened), the team has a starting point for debugging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The "is this real-time?" question.** Walks alongside every clinical recipe. Real-time monitoring has different infrastructure, different latency budgets, different failure modes, and different regulatory exposure than batch reporting. Recipes that are real-time say so explicitly; recipes that look real-time but actually run on a 15-minute batch cadence are honest about that, because clinicians who think they're getting real-time data and aren't will design workflows that fail when the assumption breaks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration with existing operational dashboards.** Forecasts are useful when they're integrated with the dashboards and decision tools that operations teams already use, not when they live in a separate "AI dashboard" that nobody opens. The architectural pattern is to push forecasts into the existing operational data warehouse and let the BI tools surface them in the views people already check. The recipes that are deployed at scale in healthcare almost always do this; the recipes that fail to be adopted often don't.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The build-versus-buy math varies by recipe.** Operational forecasting (12.1, 12.2, 12.5, 12.6) is mostly build, because the data is yours and the methods are commodity. ED arrival forecasting (12.3) is sometimes buy, especially if your ED workflow is on a vendor platform that includes forecasting natively. Vital sign monitoring (12.7) and waveform analysis (12.10) are mostly buy from regulated vendors, because the FDA pathway for a custom build is multi-year and most organizations don't have the regulatory capacity. The recipes are explicit about which math applies and why.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## What You'll Build
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m By the end of this chapter, you'll have patterns for:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Forecasting appointment volume by day and week with calibrated prediction intervals, replacing spreadsheet rules-of-thumb with methods that quantify uncertainty and support actual capacity decisions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Forecasting supply consumption across thousands of SKUs, with safety stock optimization and reorder timing that reduces both stockouts and excess inventory
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Forecasting ED arrival volumes by hour and acuity, with the hierarchical structure and operational integration that bed managers and charge nurses can actually act on
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Analyzing patient-specific lab result trajectories, with the personalized baselines and alert calibration that surface concerning trends without contributing to alert fatigue
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Forecasting hospital census by unit and service line with hierarchical reconciliation, so unit-level and system-level forecasts agree and operational dashboards stop contradicting each other
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Forecasting revenue cycle cash flow across payer types, with the data engineering and contract-aware modeling that finance teams need for working capital planning
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Continuously monitoring vital sign trajectories with patient-specific baselines, deterioration detection, and alert routing that meets the alert-fatigue tolerance of the receiving clinical team
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Modeling individual patients' disease progression trajectories with the longitudinal-and-survival joint modeling, treatment-effect handling, and clinical validation rigor that the use case demands
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Forecasting epidemic incidence with the multi-source data integration, mechanistic-plus-statistical modeling, and uncertainty communication that public health decision-makers actually need
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Analyzing high-frequency physiological waveforms with the signal processing, classification, FDA-aware deployment, and ICU workflow integration that turns raw waveforms into clinically useful information
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each recipe is self-contained, but the infrastructure compounds. The data engineering, backtesting discipline, and prediction interval calibration from 12.1 and 12.2 are foundational for every later recipe. The hierarchical forecasting infrastructure from 12.5 generalizes to 12.3 and 12.6. The streaming infrastructure from 12.7 carries into 12.10. The patient-specific baseline patterns from 12.4 are the foundation for 12.7 and 12.8. Treat the early recipes as capability investments; the later ones get faster, safer, and cheaper because of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m One last thing before we get into it. Time series in healthcare has a strange property: the simple recipes are dramatically underdeployed, and the complex recipes are oversold. There are healthcare organizations spending hundreds of thousands of dollars on AI vendor pilots for cutting-edge clinical prediction while their bed management team is using a spreadsheet that was written in 2007. The shortest path from interesting to useful in this domain, for most organizations, is to do the simple things well, build the operational muscles, and earn the right to attempt the harder ones. The complex recipes in this chapter are real, important, and worth building. They are also the wrong place to start for almost everyone. Start with the appointment volume forecast. Get the data pipeline right. Earn the backtesting discipline. Calibrate your prediction intervals. The clinical recipes will be there when you're ready.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Alright. Let's teach the computer to see patterns in time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *→ [Recipe 12.1: Appointment Volume Forecasting](chapter12.01-appointment-volume-forecasting)*
